{"award_age":64.0,"bio_image":"full\/139718249cc3337bebad2a10fe5d91f279b41f23.jpg","category":"Peace","country":"Kenya","date_of_birth":"1940-04-01T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"2011-09-25T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"female","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/d\/d8\/Wangari_Maathai.jpg\/220px-Wangari_Maathai.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Wangari_Muta_Maathai","mini_bio":"<p><b>Wangari Muta Maathai<\/b> (1 April 1940\u00a0\u2013 25 September 2011) was a Kenyan environmental and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Political_activist\" title=\"Political activist\" class=\"mw-redirect\">political activist<\/a>. She was educated in the United States at Mount St. Scholastica (<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Benedictine_College\" title=\"Benedictine College\">Benedictine College<\/a>) and the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Pittsburgh\" title=\"University of Pittsburgh\">University of Pittsburgh<\/a>, as well as the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Nairobi\" title=\"University of Nairobi\">University of Nairobi<\/a> in Kenya.<\/p><p>In the 1970s, Maathai founded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Green_Belt_Movement\" title=\"Green Belt Movement\">Green Belt Movement<\/a>, an environmental non-governmental organization focused on the planting of trees, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Environmental_conservation\" title=\"Environmental conservation\" class=\"mw-redirect\">environmental conservation<\/a>, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Women%27s_rights\" title=\"Women's rights\">women's rights<\/a>. In 1986, she was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Right_Livelihood_Award\" title=\"Right Livelihood Award\">Right Livelihood Award<\/a>, and in 2004, she became the first African woman to receive the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Peace_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Peace Prize\">Nobel Peace Prize<\/a> for \"her contribution to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Sustainable_development\" title=\"Sustainable development\">sustainable development<\/a>, democracy and peace\". Maathai was an elected <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/National_Assembly_of_Kenya\" title=\"National Assembly of Kenya\" class=\"mw-redirect\">member of Parliament<\/a> and served as assistant minister for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Natural_environment\" title=\"Natural environment\">Environment<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Natural_resource\" title=\"Natural resource\">Natural Resources<\/a> in the government of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/President_of_Kenya\" title=\"President of Kenya\">President<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mwai_Kibaki\" title=\"Mwai Kibaki\">Mwai Kibaki<\/a> between January 2003 and November 2005. Furthermore she was an Honorary Councillor of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/World_Future_Council\" title=\"World Future Council\">World Future Council<\/a>. In 2011, Maathai died of complications from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ovarian_cancer\" title=\"Ovarian cancer\">ovarian cancer<\/a>.<\/p>","name":"Wangari Muta Maathai","place_of_birth":"Ihithe  village,  Nyeri District , Kenya","place_of_death":"Nairobi, Kenya","text":"Wangari Muta Maathai , Peace, 2004","year":2004.0}